    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-29T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-29T07:00:00-05:00" n="804"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d804">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11348: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-29T20:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 29, 1937—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 29—2:26 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>974. Embassy’s 944, November 22, 10 p.m., and 958, November 26, 9 a.m. Please
                    expedite communication of following message to Japanese Ambassador: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The International Committee, which forwarded to the Japanese authorities
                            through the courtesy of the American Embassy on 22 <pb facs="0740"
                                n="733" xml:id="pg_733"/> November a proposal for a safety zone in
                            Nanking, would again respectfully request favorable consideration of its
                            proposal. In order that proper arrangements may be made for the care of
                            the thousands of civilians who have no other recourse than the proposed
                            safety zone, it is necessary that the Committee should begin its work at
                            the earliest possible moment. For humanitarian reasons therefore an
                            early reply to the Committee’s proposal is earnestly desired. (Signed)
                            John H. D. Rabe, Chairman”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Shanghai, Hankow, Peiping. Peiping kindly expedite repetition to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>For the Ambassador:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
